7":"1115–1157","1118–Female":"1118–Deceased","1140–1196":"1140–1196","1080–1141":"1080–1141","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1141":"1141","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","Hadston, Northumberland, England":"Hadston, Northumberland, England","England":"England","Hedlestone, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Héron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Herron  .","French (<b>Héron</b>): nickname for a tall, thin person, thought to resemble a heron (Old French <i>hairon</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Herron","meanings":["English: habitational name from Harome (North Yorkshire), from Old English <i>(æt thǣm) hārum</i> ‘at the (gray) stones’, dative plural of <i>hār</i> ‘gray, stone’.","English and Scottish: nickname probably for a tall, thin man with long legs, from Old French <i>hairon</i> ‘heron’, Anglo-Norman French <i>heron</i>, Middle English <i>heiroun</i>, <i>heyron</i>, <i>herne</i>, <i>heron</i>. Compare   Hearn   and   Heron  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from (Le) Héron in France (Seine-Maritime)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Héron was born in 1115, in Hadston, Northumberland, England, his father, Jordan De Héron, was 35 and his mother, Mrs Jordan de Heron, was 36. He married Maria De Ford. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1157, in England, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1115–1157":"1115–1157","1118–Female":"1118–Surnud","1140–1196":"1140–1196","1080–1141":"1080–1141","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1141":"1141","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","Hadston, Northumberland, England":"Hadston, Northumberland, England","England":"England","Hedlestone, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1115–1157":"1115–1157","1118–Female":"1118–Kuollut","1140–1196":"1140–1196","1080–1141":"1080–1141","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1141":"1141","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","Hadston, Northumberland, England":"Hadston, Northumberland, England","England":"England","Hedlestone, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"1115–1157":"1115–1157","1118–Female":"1118–Décédée","1140–1196":"1140–1196","1080–1141":"1080–1141","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1141":"1141","1196":"1196","1140":"1140",